S3 access and features: pre-signed U-R-Ls, access points, events, and hosting.

A pre-signed U-R-L grants temporary, credential-free access to one specific object. The signature in the U-R-L carries the authorization, inheriting whatever the signer is allowed to do, and it expires in at most seven days; S-T-S-signed U-R-Ls are bounded by the session. The two big uses are letting a user download a private object via a link, and letting a browser upload directly to S3 without round-tripping through your backend.

S3 Access Points are named endpoints on a bucket, each with its own policy. Instead of one increasingly tangled bucket policy serving every team, you make an analytics access point that's read-only, an app access point for the write path, and a V-P-C access point for V-P-C-only access, each with a focused policy. Event Notifications fire when objects are created, removed, restored, or transitioned, and route to S-Q-S, S-N-S, Lambda, or EventBridge. You use the direct destinations for the one-trigger-one-handler case, and EventBridge once the routing gets complex, with pattern matching, multiple targets, and replay.

For static website hosting, S3 can serve a site directly, with index and error documents on the s3-website endpoint. But production puts CloudFront in front: a custom domain, H-T-T-P-S via an A-C-M certificate, global edge caching, and Origin Access Control, or O-A-C, so the bucket stays private and only CloudFront can read it, with W-A-F at the edge. The bare endpoint is for quick internal sites; CloudFront plus O-A-C is the production default.
